        <h1>LeetCode 3542: Minimum Operations to Convert All Elements to Zero (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an array nums of size n, consisting of non-negative integers. Your task is to apply some (possibly zero) operations on the array so that all elements become 0. In one operation, you can select a subarray [i, j] (where 0 &lt;= i &lt;= j &lt; n) and set all occurrences of the minimum non-negative integer in that subarray to 0. Return the minimum number of operations required to make all elements in the array 0.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: nums = [1,2,1,2,1,2]<br>
                Output: 4<br>
                Explanation: Select subarray [0,5] with minimum 1, set all 1s to 0 → [0,2,0,2,0,2]. Select [1,1] → [0,0,0,2,0,2]. Select [3,3] → [0,0,0,0,0,2]. Select [5,5] → [0,0,0,0,0,0]. Total: 4 operations.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minOperations(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        int operations = 0;
        int n = nums.size();
        
        // Process array from left to right
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
            // Skip if already zero
            if (nums[i] == 0) {
                continue;
            }
            
            // Check if current element differs from previous non-zero element
            if (i == 0 || nums[i] != nums[i - 1]) {
                operations++;
            }
        }
        
        return operations;
    }
};</code></pre>
